= DEMO_ARMASA demonstration of some ARMASA toolbox features =
Note: DEMO_ARMASA is a program script. All variables are created in the base
workspace and can directly be accessed in the command window.
The parameters of a stationary and invertible ARMA(3,2) process are used
to generate the data. The true AR parameters are,
and the true MA parameters are,
The data used for the experiment are generated with simuarma
That gives the exact probability density for a finite record
It is better than generating a long transient
because that remains an approximation for AR processes
Every time this demo runs, new sequences of random numbers are generated.
A time series model is automatically estimated and selected from the data
using:
[ar_est ma_est sellog] = armasel(data);

The structure variable ''sellog'' provides additional information on the
selection process.
The field ''comp_time'' shows the overall computing time, which is:
seconds ****
Information on the preselection stage, where AR, MA and ARMA models are
selected, is nested in the fields ''ar'', ''ma'' and ''arma'' of ''sellog''.
For example, showing this information concerning the selection of an
optimal AR-model from the data results in,
sellog.ar =
and retrieving the estimated AR parameter vector provides,
sellog.ar.ar =
For this simple process, the same final selection result can be obtained
using a limited set of AR, MA and ARMA models as possible candidates for
selection. For example, let us limit the maximum order models to AR(100),
MA(20) and ARMA(10,9). To do this we use,
[ar_alt ma_alt sellog_alt] = armasel(y,0:100,0:20,0:10);
since candidate orders are optional input arguments for ''armasel''.

The model error ME is a measure for the accuracy of the estimated model.
The ME measures the difference between the estimated model and the true
process by,
ME = moderr(ar_est,ma_est,ar_true,ma_true,n_obs);

The model error ME can also be used to measure the distance between
two arbitrary estimated models. Here the difference between the selected
ARMA and AR models from the same data is shown.
ME_dif_ARMA_AR = moderr(sellog.arma.ar,sellog.arma.ma,sellog.ar.ar,1,n_obs);
The Power Spectral Densities of true and estimated models will now be
compared. To plot the spectrum of the true process,
is invoked without output arguments.
After turning on the hold status, a second graph can be plotted in the
figure using ''arma2psd'', while line colors are automatically varied.
The spectrum of the estimated model is added to the figure using,
True and estimated Power Spectral Density ( log-scale )
In addition, 50 values of the estimated autocorrelation function and 129
values of the estimated power spectral density are determined numerically
with,
psd_est = arma2psd(ar_est,ma_est);
cor_est = arma2cor(ar_est,ma_est,50);
The same is done for the parameter vectors of the true process.
The results of the experiment are displayed in four figures:
Figure 1 shows the true spectrum and the estimated time series spectrum.
Figure 2 shows the true and the estimated autocorrelations.
Figure 3 shows estimated accuracies of all estimated models.
Figure 4 compares the raw periodogram with the time series spectrum.
